  "texts": [
    "Programming is a complex task to find a compromise between satisfying artistic inspirations and activist intentions versus the audience tastes while balancing between too little variation and too much choice [51], and simultaneously considering outreach and practical limitations [2], such as the temporal event sequence, premiere requirements, etc.",
    "Having control over programming, however, also enables festivals to sidestep dominant and streamlined commercial distribution patterns and quickly respond to topical issues, in turn enriching the public sphere and democratizing audience access to films [52].",
    "The latter function is especially important in terms of the localities where festivals operate since the main reason festivals are typically publicly funded is that they serve national communities [10].",
    "Yet, the global media exposure generated by press representatives at the events also enables festivals to curate and diversify the international discourse on audiovisual culture by highlighting and legitimizing specific films and filmmakers, including from countries with limited production capacities, in their programming [16, 19, 52].",
    "Since festivals have the potential to generate value for both the local and international public through their programming choices, we see programming diversity as a topical research question."
